Exploring a Time Series Using Metas Prophet System

1. Using Prophet

Meta has released a time series forecasting system call prophet. This is a introductory look at the prophet system (and seeing how it compares with R).

We will analyse a default time series already installed in R. First we installed the Prophet using the command install.packages("prophet") - the default install. Then we load the package and use the built in dataset unemp from the library(astsa) which contains monthly totals of US population form 1948 to 1979. It is a time series 

library(prophet)
## Loading required package: Rcpp
## Loading required package: rlang
library(astsa)

# Load the US Unemployment dataset
data(unemp)

unemp is a time series. Use the plot(decompose()) function to get a preview of the features of the time series in R. It will show the observed data,trend, seasonal and random components.

plot(decompose(unemp))

Prophet requires the data to be in a data frame with two columns:

  • ds: the time column
  • y: the data column

Will need to load the library zoo or use the syntax ds=zoo::as.yearmon()

Unemployment_dataframe = data.frame(ds=zoo::as.yearmon(time(unemp)),y=unemp)

head(Unemployment_dataframe)
##         ds     y
## 1 Jan 1948 235.1
## 2 Feb 1948 280.7
## 3 Mar 1948 264.6
## 4 Apr 1948 240.7
## 5 May 1948 201.4
## 6 Jun 1948 240.8

It would appear that the numbers are given as 0000

Fitting the Model

Now we fit the model using prophet() This gives model with daily and weekly seasonality disabled.

FittedUnemploymentModel = prophet::prophet(Unemployment_dataframe)
## Disabling weekly seasonality. Run prophet with weekly.seasonality=TRUE to override this.
## Disabling daily seasonality. Run prophet with daily.seasonality=TRUE to override this.

Future Predictions

we first create a future dataframe for a desired forecast period of 2 years using make_future_dataframe()

Then we use the predict() function for the forecast

future = prophet::make_future_dataframe(FittedUnemploymentModel,periods=24,freq="month")

forecast = predict(FittedUnemploymentModel,future)

Now we plot the forecasted results using plot

plot(FittedUnemploymentModel,forecast, xlab="Date",ylab="Unemployed '0000")

## Can visualise it better by seeing where there are changes in trajectory
plot(FittedUnemploymentModel, forecast,xlab="Date",ylab="Unemployed '0000") + add_changepoints_to_plot(FittedUnemploymentModel)

## Plotting the forecasted components to see the forecast broken down into trend and yearly seasonality
prophet_plot_components(FittedUnemploymentModel, forecast)

Can see an overall upward trend in the numbers of unemployed, with a slight dip in the 1960s. The rate of unemployment increased faster in the 1970s - possibly due to the Oil Crisis and recession.

Based on observed seasonality, highest unemployment tends to be January/February with lowest unemployment in July/August.

Prediction for a longer period - 5 years

futurelonger = prophet::make_future_dataframe(FittedUnemploymentModel,periods=60,freq="month")
forecastlonger = predict(FittedUnemploymentModel,futurelonger)
plot(FittedUnemploymentModel,forecastlonger)

It appears that forecasting too far out into the future is not too accurate. For example the actual average unemployment number in 1982 was about 11.5 million whilst we get a predicted number of approx 10 million

2. Analysing Components

Now we analyse trends, seasonality and look at detrending and deseasonalizing

Trend

Need the library(dplyr) To see the trend

library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
trend = forecast %>% select(ds,trend)
plot(trend$ds,trend$trend,type="l",xlab="Date",ylab="trend '0000",main="Trend Component of US Unemployment")

Seasonality

To see the seasonality. NOTE: Prophet classifies seasonality as yearly, so use that in the syntax

library(dplyr)
seasonality = forecast %>% select(ds,yearly)
plot(seasonality$ds,seasonality$yearly,type="l",xlab="Date",ylab="Seasonal '0000",main="Seasonal Component of US Unemployment")

Both R and Prophet appear to give similar graphs for trend and seasonality.

3. Linear Rgression

Run a linear regression using lm() to model the growth in the series and plot

linear_model <- lm(y ~ ds, data = Unemployment_dataframe)
summary(linear_model)

plot(Unemployment_dataframe$ds, Unemployment_dataframe$y, type = "l", main = "Linear Trend in Unemp Data", xlab = "Date", ylab = "Unemp Rate")
abline(linear_model, col = "red")

The summary(linear_model) output provides details such as the slope and intercept of the model.

Regression line suggest overall upward trend in unemployment. It would appear that the model oversimplifies the data.

4. Transformations of the Data to Stabilise Variance

We will try the log transformation. To obtain the detrended data, first order differencing operator \(\nabla\) is applied to the transformed data.

We use the seasonal differencing operator \(\nabla_{12}\) on the detrended data

logUnemployemnt_dataframe=log(Unemployment_dataframe$y)

## To obtain detrended data

difflogUnemployemnt_dataframe=diff(logUnemployemnt_dataframe)

 
plot(difflogUnemployemnt_dataframe, ylab="Detrended Data")

## Deseasonalised data

diffdifflogUnemployemnt_dataframe=diff(difflogUnemployemnt_dataframe,12)

plot(diffdifflogUnemployemnt_dataframe, ylab="Detrended & Deseasonalised Data")

The application of the first differencing operator appears to remove the trend. Most of the seasonality is also taken care off by the lag operator. These adjustments provide insight into the residual behaviours.

5. Holt-Winters Exponential Smoothing

hw=HoltWinters(logUnemployemnt_dataframe)
plot(hw)

## The detrended and deseasonalised data can be plotted

detrenddeseasonhw = logUnemployemnt_dataframe - hw$fitted[,1]
plot(detrenddeseasonhw,ylab="Detrended & Deseasonalised Data")

Not much difference between logarithmic smoothing and Holt-Winters Smoothing

Holt-Winters vs Prophet

To compare Holt-Winters with Prophet, apply Holt-Winters using the forecast package on the same data

library(forecast)
## Registered S3 method overwritten by 'quantmod':
##   method            from
##   as.zoo.data.frame zoo
## 
## Attaching package: 'forecast'
## The following object is masked from 'package:astsa':
## 
##     gas
hw_model = HoltWinters(unemp)
hw_forecast = forecast(hw_model, h = 24) 
plot(hw_forecast)

## forecast from prophet
plot(FittedUnemploymentModel,forecast, xlab="Date",ylab="Unemployed '0000")

Both models effectively model trends and seasonality, but differ slightly in forecasting.

6. Summary

This provides an introductory analysis of a time series using Metas Prophet system. It covers data preparation, model fitting, future predictions, trends and seasonality, linear regression, transformations to stabilize variance. It also looks at Holt-Winters exponential smoothing, and comparison with Prophet forecasting.
